The {{nihongo|'''Nabeta Yokoanabos'''|鍋田横穴| Nabeta yokoaka}} is an {{ill|Archaeological site|en|Archaeological site|qid=Q839954|lt=Archaeological site|1=Archaeological site}} containing a cluster of late [[Kofun period]] {{nihongo|{{ill|corridor-type kofun|lt=cave tomb|kk=-type ''kofun''|ja|横穴墓|1=Yokoanabo|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/corridor-type kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokoanabo|qq=}}|横穴墓|Yokōbo}} located in what is now part of the city of {{ill|Yamaga, Kumamoto|en|Yamaga, Kumamoto|qid=Q861214|lt=Yamaga, Kumamoto|1=Yamaga, Kumamoto}}, {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}. It is significant in that many of these tombs are [[decorated kofun]] with geometric and figurative patterns painted in red on the walls of the [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]]. The site was designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 1922.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/401/2803 |title= 鍋田横穴|trans-title=Nabeta Yokoana |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=}}</ref>
==Overview== The Nabeta Yokoanabos are located on a 500-meter stretch of cliffs of {{ill|Mount Aso|en|Mount Aso|qid=Q733710|lt=Aso|1=Mount Aso}} {{ill|Tuff|en|Tuff|qid=Q484924|lt=Tuff|1=Tuff}} on the west bank of the Iwano River, a tributary of the Kikuchi River, in northern Kumamoto Prefecture. A total of 61 cave tombs have been identified, of which 16 are decorated. Tomb No. 27 is particularly noteworthy, with a double decorative border, a rectangular tomb chamber 2 meters deep and 2.5 meters wide, and a flat floor. On the left outer wall are a figure with arms and legs outstretched, a sword, a bow, an octopus-shaped quiver with six arrowheads, a knives, and a small bow with arrows nocked, and a shield. Beneath the large and small quivers is a horse carved in relief with its head facing the passage. There are many other cave groups scattered throughout Yamaga city, such as the Nagaiwa Yokoanabos and the Shiro Yokoanabos. Currently, the surrounding area has been developed as Nabeta Recreation Forest Park.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.iwaki.fukushima.jp/map/1315/002556.html |script-title=ja:施設案内「考古資料館」 |trans-title=Facilities: Archaeological Museum |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Iwaki, Fukushima|Iwaki City]] |accessdate=25 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020200143/http://www.city.iwaki.fukushima.jp/map/1315/002556.html |archivedate=20 October 2012 }}</ref>
